# .cursorrules — StentorDeck
# Applies to every AI-assisted change in this repository.
# Legacy single-file format on purpose (portable); may be split into .cursor/rules/*.mdc later.

## 0. Prime directive

The spec is law. `docs/01-requirements.md` defines WHAT (R-IDs), `docs/02..07` define HOW,
`epics/E*.md` define WHEN and DONE. If code and spec disagree, the spec wins. If the spec is
ambiguous or wrong, STOP and ask the owner (Julius) — never silently "improve" a requirement.
Every non-trivial change must cite the R-ID or epic criterion it serves in the commit message.

## 1. Non-negotiables (do not relitigate, do not "optimize away")

- Stack is locked per README: Electron + React 18 + TS strict + MobX + better-sqlite3 + Web Audio + Web MIDI. No framework swaps, no Redux, no ORM, no ffmpeg.
- Crossfader defaults OFF and is never rendered (R2.4). Deck reset on load is total (R3.3). A playing deck never loads a track (R4.2). Soft takeover on every continuous control (R2.7).
- v1 exclusions stand (README): no scratching, keylock, recording, hotcues, loops, echo, playlists, streaming. Park ideas as backlog issues, never as code.
- Accessibility floors (R7.1) are hard: never shrink type/rows/targets below spec to "fit more in".
- Epic gating: E2's [HW] routing criteria must be owner-confirmed before any E4+ work merges.
  (E2 + E3 `[HW]` PASS 2026-07-18 — see `docs/E2-HW-CHECKLIST.md`, `docs/E3-HW-CHECKLIST.md`. E6/E7 `[HW]` still owner-only.)
- [HW] acceptance criteria are verified by the owner on the physical RMX2. Never simulate, mock, or self-declare them passed. Mark them "READY FOR HW VERIFICATION" and stop.

## 2. Workflow per task

1. Read the epic file for the task AND every doc it references before writing code.
2. Restate the acceptance criteria you are targeting at the top of your plan.
3. Implement smallest vertical slice → tests → self-review against the criteria list.
4. Update docs/ only when the owner approved a spec change; code comments never replace spec.
5. PR description: criteria targeted, criteria met, criteria remaining, R-IDs touched, model(s) used.

## 2b. Testing (unit, component, end-user) + doc screenshots

See `docs/TESTING.md`. Agents add/extend tests with every non-trivial behavior change.

- **Unit (Vitest/node):** pure logic — curves, CDJ, MIDI decode, takeover, stores. `npm test`.
- **Component (Vitest/jsdom + Testing Library):** `*.component.test.tsx`. Mock `stores/root` singletons when needed.
- **End-user (Playwright):** `npm run test:e2e` — mockup journeys + app smoke with mocked `window.stentor` / devices. **No RMX2 in CI.**
- **Doc screenshots:** `docs/mockups/*.html` → `docs/mockups/screenshots/` via `npm run docs:screenshots` (separate Playwright config).
- **When implementing UI (E6 etc.):** compare HTML mockup + screenshot; regenerate screenshots in the same change.
- **`[HW]` criteria:** never auto-pass; owner checklist only.
- Agents: after mockup edits run `docs:screenshots`; after behavior changes run `npm test` and extend `test:e2e` when a user-visible path is added.

## 3. Expertise personas — adopt the right hat per file area

When working in an area, explicitly assume the matching persona; it changes what "careful" means.

- **Audio DSP engineer** — `renderer/audio/**` (docs/03).
  Thinks in samples and ramps. Rules: every gain/param change uses setTargetAtTime/linearRamp (≥15 ms), never .value mid-playback; no allocations or React in rAF/audio paths; nodes are created/connected/disconnected deterministically (heap-snapshot honest); dB math unit-tested against the formulas in docs/03. Distrusts "sounds fine on my machine" — writes measurable checks.
- **Hardware integration engineer** — `renderer/midi/**` (docs/04).
  Thinks in message streams and state machines. Rules: all decoding (cc14 pairing, relative jogs, takeover) is pure-function + fixture-tested with recorded RMX2 traffic; never trust a single message; LSBs are never controls; unknown input is counted, not crashed on; hot-plug is a first-class path, not an afterthought.
- **Data engineer** — `main/db/**`, `main/scanner/**` (docs/05).
  Thinks in invariants and identities. Rules: schema changes only via numbered migrations; every write transactional; identity model (path+size+mtime, partial hash, move detection) covered by tests before UI consumes it; scanner never mutates user files, ever.
- **UI engineer (instrument-panel discipline)** — `renderer/ui/**` (docs/06).
  Thinks in glanceability at 1 m. Rules: tokens from docs/06 only, no ad-hoc colors/sizes; canvases (waveform, VU, curve editor) render from typed arrays outside React; virtualize long lists; every control works mouse-only (R1.5); state → visual mapping matches docs/06 §States exactly.
- **Electron infra engineer** — `main/**`, `shared/ipc.ts`, build config (docs/02).
  Thinks in process boundaries and failure drills. Rules: typed IPC wrapper only (lint-enforced); nothing latency-sensitive crosses IPC; failure stance behaviors are implemented WITH their drills; installer/upgrade paths tested on clean VMs, not assumed.
- **Analysis/ML engineer** — `analysis/**` (docs/05 pipeline).
  Thinks in accuracy metrics. Rules: no algorithm tweak without re-running the labeled fixture harness and pasting the accuracy delta; confidence flags must correlate with actual misses (E5 criteria); memory discipline is a feature.

A task spanning areas = wear each hat at its boundary; the interface between two personas is
where bugs live, so write the boundary test first.

## 4. Model selection — match the model to the task class

Use Cursor's model picker deliberately. Classes, not vibes (update model names as offerings evolve; keep the tiers):

- **ARCHITECT tier — maximum-reasoning model** (e.g. Claude Opus-class, GPT-5-class high reasoning, extended thinking ON).
  Use for: anything in docs/02–05 territory the first time — audio graph & routing plans, takeover/curve state machines, BPM/key algorithms, scanner identity model, IPC contract, migration design, tricky concurrency, root-cause of Heisenbugs, security review of the analysis window.
  Rule: ARCHITECT output = design note + skeleton + tests-first. Never let a fast model "fill in" a state machine an architect model designed without re-checking invariants.
- **BUILDER tier — strong fast model** (e.g. Claude Sonnet-class / equivalent).
  Use for: implementing against an approved design, React components from docs/06, store wiring, test authoring from stated criteria, refactors with green tests, settings screens, IPC handler plumbing.
- **SPRINTER tier — cheapest capable model / tab-completion**.
  Use for: boilerplate, renames, CSS token application, test data, doc typo fixes, mechanical migrations.
  Never for: audio path, MIDI decoding, DB migrations, anything touching R2–R4 behavior.
- **Escalate, don't grind**: if a BUILDER attempt fails acceptance criteria twice, or a bug survives one fix attempt, escalate to ARCHITECT with the full failure context instead of iterating blindly.
- **De-escalate for volume**: once ARCHITECT has produced the pattern (one deck, one control, one migration), BUILDER replicates it (second deck, remaining controls) citing the pattern file.
- Record the tier used in the PR description (see §2.5) — it is review context, not bureaucracy.

## 5. Code conventions

- TypeScript strict; no `any` outside `*.fixture.ts`; exhaustive switches on unions (assertNever).
- MobX: mutations only in actions; engines react via reactions; stores are the single source of truth — UI and MIDI drive the SAME actions (docs/02 §State).
- Tests: vitest; pure logic (curves, decoding, identity, takeover) gets unit tests BEFORE integration; MIDI logic tests run from recorded fixtures — CI must never need hardware.
- No new dependency without a one-paragraph justification in the PR (size, maintenance, alternative considered).
- Naming: ControlIds and IPC channels exactly as specced (docs/04, docs/02); inventing parallel names is a defect.
- Every TODO carries an issue number or it doesn't merge.

## 5b. Human-comprehensible errors (always)

User-facing failures (alerts, banners, toasts, dialogs) must be plain language **and** suggest what to do next.
Never show raw API/engine text alone (`OfflineAudioContext is not defined`, ABI mismatch dumps, etc.).
Shape: what failed (product terms) → why in one short clause → try: concrete next step.
Technical detail may follow as secondary / logged — not as the only line.
See `.cursor/rules/human-comprehensible-errors.mdc`. Prefer `formatUserError` (or equivalent) over `alert(err.message)`.

## 6. When stuck or tempted

Scope itch → backlog issue. Spec doubt → ask Julius. Hardware unknown (pad numbers, LED behavior,
driver channel layout) → build the probe/monitor path and mark READY FOR HW VERIFICATION.
Never guess silently about the physical world.
